Sexual dimorphism is evident in that females are larger than males (
Table 3
). Males have vocal slits and keratinized nuptial pads on the dorsal and inner surfaces of the thumb and of Finger III, in which they are more abundant at the proximal phalanx. The forelimbs are relatively long and slender only in females, but they are short with a stout muscular area in males (
Table 3
); there are significant differences in RDUL between males and females ( RDUL Student’s t -test, t = 4.4105 , df = 13 , P < 0.0007 ). Males lack coni and nearly lack spiculae, whereas females have coni and spiculae.

